      <h3>
        How To Use The Earthquake Visualization Tool
      </h3>
      <p>
      First off, if you have windows you should be able to <%= link_to "download the
      stand alone executable", earthquakeexecutable_path %> and run the program. There is nothing to install, just run it and wait 30 seconds
      or so for the entire dataset from the years 1973-2011 to load into the program. If
      you have a Mac and you wish to compile the source code check <%= link_to "this page", earthquakesource_path %> out.
      <br/> 
      <br/> 
      Once it is running you will notice there are three viewing areas. The largest
      viewing area is the main view. Just about all the tools on the left panel
      affect all three views except the map location comobo box. This feature was
      meant to only affect the main view so you could set the two smaller views
      map location then choose a specific view in the main one and see the earthquake
      simulations from three different areas at once. To move around in the views,
      the first mouse button while rotate the view, the second mouse button will zoom in 
      and out, and if you have a mouse wheel it will zoom when scrolled and pan when clicked.
      <br/>
      <br/>
      <%= link_to image_tag("EarthquakeImages/DepthValues.jpg", :height => "225px", :id => "below-gallery"),
        'images/EarthquakeImages/DepthValues.jpg', :rel => "prettyPhoto[earthquake_screens]"%>
        <%= image_tag("EarthquakeImages/DepthValues.jpg", :class => "earthquake_screen") %>
      While using the program the most commonly changed values will most likely be
      the depth and the magnitude. So I created two legends in the program to tell what the current values are. The
      depth legend is inside all three viewing areas. It is the white line with
      the labels min and max depth. The second legend is the color bar which
      shows the magnitude level. Generally the darker the color the lower the
      magnitude and the brighter or lighter the color the higher the magnitude.
      There are also text boxes on the left showing the same information the legends
      show and more.
      <br/> 
      <br/>
      Besides the magnitude and depth, other values can be modified on the dataset such as
      color, year, and location. The color is changeable for two purposes, color blindness and
      different colors schemes always makes things more fun! The user can view specific years 
      of the dataset. This is useful when doing playback. Users can choose a range of years
      and hit the play button and the program will cycle through one year every second. The
      user also has the option of changing how fast the cycle is and how many years each cycle
      covers.
      </p>
    </div>
